    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix sequence number validation and logging in PDCP layer\n\n### Summary\nThe PDCP sequence manager had incorrect logging format strings and redundant validation checks that could cause issues with debugging and performance. When the pdcp_is_seq_num_size_valid() function was called with an invalid sequence number size, the log message would be malformed due to a missing closing parenthesis, making it difficult to parse error logs.\n\nAdditionally, the pdcp_is_seq_num_valid() function contained a redundant check for negative sequence numbers even though the parameter is unsigned, and the maximum sequence number calculation used an unnecessarily complex bit-shifting approach.\n\nThis fix corrects the logging format string, removes redundant validation logic, and simplifies the sequence number calculations.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/LAYER2/PDCP_v10.1.0/pdcp_sequence_manager.c`: \n  * Fixed missing closing parenthesis in log message format string in pdcp_is_seq_num_size_valid()\n  * Removed redundant seq_num >= 0 check in pdcp_is_seq_num_valid() since uint16_t cannot be negative\n  * Simplified pdcp_calculate_max_seq_num_for_given_size() implementation\n  * Streamlined function returns for better readability\n\n### Reproduction Steps\nTo reproduce the original logging issue:\n1. Configure a PDCP entity with an invalid sequence number size (not 5, 7, or 12)\n2. Call pdcp_is_seq_num_size_valid() on this entity\n3. Check the PDCP warning logs - the message will be missing the closing parenthesis\n\nThe malformed log entries would appear as:\n\"Incoming SN size is invalid! (Expected: {5 | 7 | 12}, Received: 15\\n\"\n\nInstead of the correct format:\n\"Incoming SN size is invalid! (Expected: {5 | 7 | 12}, Received: 15)\\n\"\n\nPerformance impact from the redundant validation was minimal but measurable in high-throughput scenarios.\n"
}